22aa41dd-2048-44aa-ad92-298adefb9989	Grade 6 Science .pdf	pdf	application/pdf	100181	D:\\Tekjoy\\chatbot\\uploads\\20251011042756_Grade 6 Science .pdf	\N	\N	2025-10-11 11:27:56.133443+07	2025-10-11 11:27:56.188302+07	4aa03ac3-8e9b-4bcf-8f9a-0c46f9a20c4f	uploaded	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	{}	a0a00953-72d4-4422-84b0-882a0938112b	\N	Grade 6 Science Learning Path \n(Lessons 1-35) \n \nLesson 1: Numbers and Operations \n●​ Vocabulary: Students are introduced to the four basic mathematical \noperations: Addition, Subtraction, Multiplication, and Division. This lesson \nserves as a foundation for all other math topics. \n \nLesson 2: Positive and Negative Numbers \n●​ Vocabulary: An integer is defined as a whole number that can be positive, \nnegative, or zero. \n●​ Practice: Students apply their knowledge of positive and negative numbers to \nsolve real-world problems. They learn that deposits are positive and \nwithdrawals are negative in a bank account, and that diving is represented by \nnegative numbers while rising is represented by positive numbers. \n○​ Examples: Calculating the final price of a stock after gains and losses, \nor finding a submarine's final depth after a series of dives and rises. \n \nLesson 3: Place Values \n●​ Vocabulary: A digit is a single number. \n●​ Practice: Students use place values to solve a secret code puzzle. The clues \nrequire them to identify the value of a digit in various places, from the millions \ndown to the ten thousandths. \n \nLesson 4: Ordering and Rounding \n●​ Rounding: Rounding to a decimal place is just like rounding whole numbers. \n\n\n●​ Practice: Students learn to round numbers like 45.3467 to 1, 2, or 3 decimal \nplaces. They also use these skills to estimate answers to problems. \n \nLesson 5: Algebra Introduction \n●​ Vocabulary: This lesson defines the fundamental parts of an algebraic \nexpression: \n○​ Variable: A letter that represents a value that can change. \n○​ Constant: A value in an expression that is fixed. \n○​ Expression: A combination of terms. \n○​ Equation: A statement that two expressions are equal. \n●​ Practice: Students identify the different parts of an equation like 4a+5b−20=3. \n \nLesson 6: Terms & Variables \n●​ Vocabulary: A sequence is a list of numbers in order. \n●​ Practice: Students simplify expressions by combining like terms. \n○​ Example: Simplifying 3a+6a+12a to get 21a. \n \nLesson 7: Algebraic Substitution \n●​ Vocabulary: In algebra, substitution is the process of putting numbers in the \nplace of letters. This is especially helpful when using formulae. \n●​ Practice: Students solve equations by replacing variables with given values. \n○​ Example: Solve for an equation if x=2 or if a=4 and b=3. \n \nLesson 8: Simplifying Expressions \n●​ Practice: Students learn to combine variables. They use​\n coefficients for addition and indices for multiplication. \n○​ Examples: Simplifying expressions like 2x2+3x2 or 4a+2b2+3b2. \n\n\n \nLesson 9: Square Numbers \n●​ Vocabulary: An index (or plural indices) is a number that shows how many \ntimes a base number is multiplied by itself. \n●​ Practice: Students learn to evaluate expressions with indices, such as 82=64. \n \nLesson 10: Square Roots \n●​ Vocabulary: Square roots are the opposite of indices. The symbol for a square \nroot is​\n \n​. \n●​ Practice: Students learn that the square root of 121 is 11 because 112=121. \n \nLesson 11: Estimation 1 \n●​ Vocabulary: Estimation is when you guess what a value should be close to. \n●​ Practice: Students work with a table showing the number of visitors to a zoo \nover six months to practice estimation skills. \n \nLesson 12: Estimation 2 \n●​ Vocabulary: Estimation is defined as guessing "more or less" what a value \nshould be. \n●​ Practice: Students practice rounding numbers up or down and identify what \nposition a rounded number has been rounded to. They also estimate answers \nto problems involving multiplication, subtraction, and division. \n \n\n\nLesson 13: Brackets & Formulae \n●​ Practice: When solving for a variable, students learn to use BIDMAS to \nsimplify expressions and SAMDIB to move non-variable numbers to the other \nside of the equal sign. \n \nLesson 14: Types of Angles \n●​ Vocabulary: An obtuse angle is more than 90° but less than 180°. A​\n reflex angle is greater than 180°. \n \nLesson 15: Parallel Lines \n●​ Vocabulary: With parallel lines, corresponding (F) angles are equal.​\n Co-interior (C) angles add up to 180°. \n●​ Practice: Students calculate the values of missing angles in diagrams with \nparallel lines. \n \nLesson 16: Triangles \n●​ Vocabulary: This lesson covers the main types of triangles: scalene (three \ndifferent side lengths) ,​\n isosceles (two equal angles and two equal sides), and equilateral (all sides \nand angles equal). \n \nLesson 17: Interior & Exterior Angles \n●​ Vocabulary: An interior angle is an angle inside a shape. An​\n exterior angle is an angle outside a shape. \n \n\n\nLesson 18: Quadrilaterals 1 \n●​ Vocabulary: Students learn to identify different types of quadrilaterals: \nSquare, Rectangle, Trapezium, Rhombus, and Parallelogram. \n \nLesson 19: Quadrilaterals 2 \n●​ Vocabulary: This lesson introduces more specific quadrilaterals like Irregular, \nDelta, and Kite. \n●​ Practice: Students write descriptions of shapes to explain why they are or are \nnot quadrilaterals. \n \nLesson 20: 3D Shapes 1 \n●​ Vocabulary: Students are introduced to basic 3D shapes: Cube, Cuboid, \nSphere, and Cylinder. \n \nLesson 21: 3D Shapes 2 \n●​ Vocabulary: This lesson covers additional 3D shapes: Square-based Pyramid, \nTriangular-based Pyramid, Triangular Prism, and Cone. \n \nLesson 22: 3D Shapes 3 \n●​ Vocabulary: Students learn the terminology for the parts of 3D shapes: Faces \nare the sides of a shape, Edges are the outer lines, and Vertices are the points \nor corners. \n●​ Practice: Students are asked to identify and label the faces, edges, and \nvertices of various 3D shapes. \n \n\n\nLesson 23: Geometric Nets \n●​ Vocabulary: A net is a 2D representation of a 3D shape. You can cut and fold \na net to make a 3D shape. \n●​ Practice: Students practice drawing the nets of different shapes. \n \nLesson 24: Bar Charts \n●​ Vocabulary: An axis is a line used to measure data on a graph. The​\n y-axis is vertical, and the x-axis is horizontal. \n \nLesson 25: Line Graphs \n●​ Vocabulary: A line graph is used to display information that changes over \ntime. \n●​ Practice: Students analyze line graphs showing rainfall over a year to answer \nquestions and describe changes in data. \n \nLesson 26: Pictographs \n●​ Vocabulary: A pictograph is a way to show data using images. \n \nLesson 27: Averages 1 \n●​ Vocabulary: An average is a single number used to represent a large set of \nnumbers. \n●​ Practice: Students learn to find the mean and median of a set of numbers. \n \nLessons 28-35 \n\n\nThe remaining lessons appear to be review sessions that consolidate previously \nlearned material. Based on the file titles, here is a breakdown of the topics likely \ncovered in each lesson: \n●​ Lessons 28-30: Averages (likely covering mean, median, mode, and range). \n●​ Lesson 31: Review of Geometric Nets. \n●​ Lesson 32: Review of Bar Charts. \n●​ Lesson 33: Review of Line Graphs. \n●​ Lesson 34: Review of Pictographs. \n●​ Lesson 35: Review of Averages. \n \n \n \n	\N	\N	/uploads/20251011042756_Grade 6 Science .pdf	6913	1089
